SIMPLE: trump
RECORDS: 6

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Trump
<hw>Trump</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>trumpe</ets>,
<ets>trompe</ets>, F. <ets>trompe</ets>; probably fr. L.
<ets>triumphare</ets> to triumph, to exult, hence, probably, to make a
joyous sound or noise. See <er>Triumph</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos> &
<pos>n.</pos>, and cf. <er>Trombone</er>, <er>Tromp</er>, <er>Trump</er>
at cards, <er>Trumpery</er>, <er>Trumpet</er>, <er>Trunk</er> a
proboscis.]</ety> <def>A wind instrument of music; a trumpet, or sound
of a trumpet; -- used chiefly in Scripture and poetry.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We shall all be changed, in a moment, in the twinkling of an eye,
at the last <qex>trump</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>1 Cor. xv. 51,
52.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The wakeful <qex>trump</qex> of doom.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trump</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Trump
<hw>Trump</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>tromper</ets>. See
<er>Trump</er> a trumpet.]</ety> <def>To blow a trumpet.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Wyclif (Matt. vi. 2).</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trump</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Trump
<hw>Trump</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[A corruption of <ets>triumph</ets>,
F. <ets>triomphe</ets>. See <er>Triumph</er>, and cf. <er>Trump</er> a
trumpet.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A winning card; one of a particular
suit (usually determined by chance for each deal) any card of which
takes any card of the other suits.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An old game with cards, nearly the same as whist; --
called also <altname>ruff</altname>.</def> <rj><au>Decker.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A good fellow; an excellent person.</def>
<mark>[Slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Alfred is a <qex>trump</qex>, I think you say.</q>
<rj><qau>Thackeray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>To put to one's trumps</b></col>, <it>or</it>
<col><b>To put on one's trumps</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to force to the
last expedient, or to the utmost exertion.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But when kings come so low as to fawn upon philosophy, which
before they neither valued nor understood, it is a sign that fails not,
they are then <qex>put to their</qex> last <qex>trump</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Put</qex> the housekeeper <qex>to her trumps</qex> to
accommodate them.</q> <rj><qau>W. Irving.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trump</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Trump
<hw>Trump</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Trumped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Trumping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To play a trump card when one of
another suit has been led.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trump</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Trump
<hw>Trump</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To play a trump card upon; to take
with a trump card; <as>as, she <ex>trumped</ex> the first
trick</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trump</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Trump
<hw>Trump</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>tromper</ets> to deceive,
in OF., to blow a trumpet, <ets>se tromper de</ets> to mock. See
<er>Trump</er> a trumpet.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To trick, or impose
on; to deceive.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧To trick or
<xex>trump</xex> mankind.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To impose unfairly; to palm off.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Authors have been <qex>trumped</qex> upon us.</q> <rj><qau>C.
Leslie.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To trump up</b></col>, <cd>to devise; to collect with
unfairness; to fabricate; as, <xex>to trump up</xex> a
charge.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trumpery</ent>⟦br⟧
